WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:13.220 --> 00:00:14.806
Professor David Blight:
This week you're reading

00:00:14.806 --> 00:00:18.785
Hospital Sketches,
the short and in some ways

00:00:18.785 --> 00:00:25.890
extraordinary little novel,
written by Louisa May Alcott,

00:00:25.890 --> 00:00:30.041
based upon her--Louisa May
Alcott of Little Women

00:00:30.041 --> 00:00:34.600
fame, if you happen to have
grown up on that book,

00:00:34.600 --> 00:00:40.024
daughter of Bronson Alcott,
a famous and extremely

00:00:40.024 --> 00:00:46.444
eccentric New England reformer
and utopian--but she went to

00:00:46.444 --> 00:00:51.547
war,
as a young nurse--couldn't stay

00:00:51.547 --> 00:01:00.117
away--and she kept her sketches
about her experiences of a young

00:01:00.117 --> 00:01:07.599
woman confronting the horror of
Civil War hospitals.

00:01:07.599 --> 00:01:12.747
This is a photograph of--it is
not Louisa May Alcott,

00:01:12.747 --> 00:01:18.785
I don't think--of one of those
young nurses sitting in a Civil

00:01:18.785 --> 00:01:25.950
War hospital in 1863,
probably writing a letter;

00:01:25.950 --> 00:01:32.615
they spent a lot of their time
writing letters for sick or

00:01:32.615 --> 00:01:37.970
dying or wounded soldiers.
I think what you can find in

00:01:37.970 --> 00:01:41.388
Alcott's novel,
among other things--it's almost

00:01:41.388 --> 00:01:44.360
like a descriptive documentary
novel;

00:01:44.360 --> 00:01:48.915
it's almost like she summed up
her diary--is the human

00:01:48.915 --> 00:01:52.010
encounter, particularly a
woman's,

00:01:52.010 --> 00:01:59.411
a young woman's encounter with
what war does to the human body,

00:01:59.411 --> 00:02:05.060
the human psyche,
to human beings.

00:02:05.060 --> 00:02:09.267
Now, good Lord,
it is eighteen years ago,

00:02:09.267 --> 00:02:15.157
Ken Burns produced--can it
really be?--a series on Public

00:02:15.157 --> 00:02:19.680
Television called The Civil
War,

00:02:19.680 --> 00:02:24.449
as every opening of it says,
brought to you by General

00:02:24.449 --> 00:02:27.969
Motors.
Nine episodes and eleven hours,

00:02:27.969 --> 00:02:32.689
garnered the largest Public
Television audience ever.

00:02:32.689 --> 00:02:36.924
The estimate was that the first
time through about thirty

00:02:36.924 --> 00:02:41.385
million Americans watched it,
and then it's been rerun many,

00:02:41.385 --> 00:02:45.054
many times.
I went to Germany to teach for

00:02:45.054 --> 00:02:49.530
a year in 1992 and '93,
and when I arrived in the Fall

00:02:49.530 --> 00:02:52.182
of 1992,
on German National Television

00:02:52.182 --> 00:02:55.923
they were running the Ken Burns
film series, all eleven hours of

00:02:55.923 --> 00:02:59.310
it,
dubbed into German.

00:02:59.310 --> 00:03:03.912
And it was weird,
because there was one male

00:03:03.912 --> 00:03:09.050
voice and one female voice for
all the voices.

00:03:09.050 --> 00:03:11.720
And of course one of the
tricks, or one of the

00:03:11.720 --> 00:03:15.163
techniques, one of the quite
brilliant techniques of Burns'

00:03:15.163 --> 00:03:18.664
film was the many different
voices he used--Garrison Keillor

00:03:18.664 --> 00:03:21.618
for Walt Whitman,
Sam Waterson for Abraham

00:03:21.618 --> 00:03:25.722
Lincoln, et cetera--voices that
you, in many ways--or Americans

00:03:25.722 --> 00:03:29.760
in many ways--were comfortable
with in their living rooms.

00:03:29.760 --> 00:03:32.135
They knew Sam Waterson;
they didn't know him as well as

00:03:32.135 --> 00:03:34.160
they know him now from Law
&amp; Order;

00:03:34.160 --> 00:03:37.448
but they knew Garrison
Keillor's voice,

00:03:37.448 --> 00:03:41.342
and when Garrison Keillor came
on every night,

00:03:41.342 --> 00:03:44.468
it was Walt Whitman.
At any rate,

00:03:44.468 --> 00:03:48.400
I was astonished at the
reaction in Germany.

00:03:48.400 --> 00:03:52.083
There were articles in the
paper, editorials and so on and

00:03:52.083 --> 00:03:54.542
so on.
I had one German student come

00:03:54.542 --> 00:03:57.757
up to me one day,
after watching an episode of it

00:03:57.757 --> 00:04:00.370
and listening to one of my
lectures,

00:04:00.370 --> 00:04:04.210
and he said,
"Why were there so many sunsets

00:04:04.210 --> 00:04:08.050
and moon rises in that
documentary film?"

00:04:08.050 --> 00:04:12.689
I said, "Wellâ€¦"--he
caught me off guard.

00:04:12.689 --> 00:04:15.270
I said, "Well it's a good
question."

00:04:15.270 --> 00:04:19.398
Probably because Burns is a
sentimental filmmaker,

00:04:19.398 --> 00:04:24.199
and there's a great deal of
sentiment in the structure,

00:04:24.199 --> 00:04:29.860
and in the music and in the
mode of that film series.

00:04:29.860 --> 00:04:34.604
And I defy you to watch one or
two hours and not be humming be

00:04:34.604 --> 00:04:38.960
the "Ashokan Farewell" in the
shower the next morning.

00:04:50.350 --> 00:04:55.835
It is a haunting violin.
It wasn't, as some people say,

00:04:55.835 --> 00:04:58.930
written for that film series,
it's much older.

00:04:58.930 --> 00:05:02.842
At any rate,
it is assigned in the course,

00:05:02.842 --> 00:05:08.403
at least major parts of it.
You can access it--I'm actually

00:05:08.403 --> 00:05:12.640
going to assign you episodes two
through nine;

00:05:12.640 --> 00:05:18.394
that's eight out of the nine.
If you skip one or two only the

00:05:18.394 --> 00:05:20.450
gods will know,
I'm sure, but they will know.

00:05:24.009 --> 00:05:28.044
It is all available on the
Internet, at Yale,

00:05:28.044 --> 00:05:32.391
through the Film Archive.
How many of you have done this

00:05:32.391 --> 00:05:35.699
before for courses?
Fabulous, you've done this.

